In my experience I would say the warrior is much easier overall due to more innate bonuses and less buttons to press and timing and rules to learn... (example: Shadowknights can both travel up and DOWN the hate list while warriors can only go UP save by dying, another example would be learning spellbased feign pulling... = art form) but when it comes to &quot;tanking&quot; the two are quite similar...  keep the mob beating on you and know the following points in order to do it.  Shadowknights have more tricks to keep hate....but it requires a much greater understanding of what you are doing to make it work to your benefit for very long.  Warriors have an easier time not dying/losing hate.<br>
<br>
The taunt button when pressed runs a check against the level differential between you and the mob and your taunt skill.  If successful, the taunt button moves you to the HIGHEST position in the mobs hate list and changes your numerical figure to be OLDHIGHEST+1... (there are now some who figure that its more than +1 now, but no one can really know for sure) That means if someone is 1000 points higher than you that you would gain 1001 hate with a single successful press. (success seems to be 60-80% depending on mob level for a 65 Shadowknight -this is without spellcasting)<br>
<br>
Now assuming you have attack on, and are closest to the mob, your melee damage potential will raise you higher in numerical value...  but note the rogue next to him is also building hate... and the Wizard behind him...  A warriors job is to stay higher on the positional list than those two...<br>
<br>
Now lets throw in yet another curve.... range seems to currently affect how much of that numerical hate is &quot;considered&quot; by a mob in order to place them on the positional hate list. (the mob usually beats on the top guy on the POSITIONAL list... and checks at some unknown time period for who it should be beating on)<br>
<br>
When the &quot;considered&quot; numerical value exceeds the value of the next highest, the positional value will change and the mob will begin hitting the new hate leader at the next hatelist check.<br>
<br>
Lets say warrior_01 has aggro at 3000 aggro, and wiz_01 nukes for 500 hate when he is at 3500aggro (2600 seen due to range), the wiz has a chance to take aggro because he is 100 points ahead... but if the &quot;listcheck&quot; doesn't come up before the warrior closes the hate gap, the mob won't change targets.  if the mob checks during this time, the mob will either summon or move towards the wizard...  <br>
<br>
lets say the mob moves closer to the wizard and makes it so that the range modifier is lessened now..  making the wizard's &quot;considered&quot; hate value 3700...  the warrior must succeed at TAUNT skill or the wizard is soon going to be 1000 points ahead and guaranteed to be beat on until low HP, and then frenzied on (+insane number of considered hate)  If TAUNT is successful, the warrior gains the CONSIDERED value +1....  but if the mob moves closer to the wiz again, he is going to have a chance to lose it once more!<br>
<br>
mashing taunt is dumb because of the TIMING of pressing it... it has a reuse time... and that 6 seconds of not begin able to press it means the mob gets away and makes a puddle out of the &quot;insert robed class here&quot; because of the limited range on TAUNT and the fact that the mob is remembering just how much he hates that robe.  Remember TAUNT skill has a maximum effective range, and when the mob quads for 1000, anyone without a CH cycle on them is dead in a hurry.<br>
<br>
there is NO skill or spell in the game better at generating snap-hate than TAUNT...  the problem is that most people don't understand it, and forget it has this problem about range and timing.<br>
<br>
Taunt is SO much better than 200 hate...  <br>
<br>
Shadowknights have spells that deal 600 hate irresistable...  Taunt is capable of SO much more.<br>
<br>
Slow is around 1000 hate (two casts of the 510pt SK hate spell pulls off of a slow)<br>
<br>
mez is around 500-600 ish<br>
<br>
Snare is around 1000ish (two casts of 510)<br>
<br>
Remember that spells such as EB and Terror are NUMERICAL hate.... not positional....  thus its only considered to raise you in the positional list if your numerical value is greater than someone else's.<br>
<br>
taunt is POSITIONAL and thus gives a variable amount of hate.<br>
<br>
